5 SECTION 3. G.S. 25-9-104 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 25-9-104. Control of deposit account.
7 (a) Requirements for control. – Control. – A secured party has control of a deposit
8 account if:if any of the following applies:
9 (1) The secured party is the bank with which the deposit account is
10 maintained;maintained.
11 (2) The debtor, secured party, and bank have agreed in an authenticated a signed
12 record that the bank will comply with instructions originated by the secured
13 party directing disposition of the funds in the deposit account without further
14 consent by the debtor; ordebtor.
15 (3) The secured party becomes the bank's customer with respect to the deposit
16 account.
17 (4) Another person, other than the debtor, does either of the following:
18 a. Has control of the deposit account and acknowledges that it has control
19 on behalf of the secured party.
20 b. Obtains control of the deposit account after having acknowledged that
21 it will obtain control of the deposit account on behalf of the secured
22 party.
23 (b) Debtor's right to direct disposition. – Right to Direct Disposition. – A secured party
24 that has satisfied subsection (a) of this section has control, even if the debtor retains the right to
25 direct the disposition of funds from the deposit account."
26 SECTION 4. G.S. 25-9-105 reads as rewritten:
27 "§ 25-9-105. Control of electronic chattel paper.copy of record evidencing chattel paper.
28 (a) General Rule: Control of Electronic Chattel Paper. – A secured party has control of
29 electronic chattel paper if a system employed for evidencing the transfer of interests in the chattel
30 paper reliably establishes the secured party as the person to which the chattel paper was assigned.
31 (b) Specific Facts Giving Control. – A system satisfies subsection (a) of this section if
32 the record or records comprising the chattel paper are created, stored, and assigned in such a
33 manner that:
34 (1) A single authoritative copy of the record or records exists which is unique,
35 identifiable, and, except as otherwise provided in subdivisions (4), (5), and (6)
36 of this section, unalterable;
37 (2) The authoritative copy identifies the secured party as the assignee of the
38 record or records;
39 (3) The authoritative copy is communicated to and maintained by the secured
40 party or its designated custodian;
41 (4) Copies or amendments that add or change an identified assignee of the
42 authoritative copy can be made only with the consent of the secured party;
43 (5) Each copy of the authoritative copy and any copy of a copy is readily
44 identifiable as a copy that is not the authoritative copy; and
45 (6) Any amendment of the authoritative copy is readily identifiable as authorized
46 or unauthorized.
47 (a) General Rule for Control of Electronic Copy of Record Evidencing Chattel Paper. –
48 A purchaser has control of an authoritative electronic copy of a record evidencing chattel paper
49 if a system employed for evidencing the assignment of interests in the chattel paper reliably
50 establishes the purchaser as the person to which the authoritative electronic copy was assigned.
